      <memberdef kind="function" id="classOpenSkyhawk_1_1I2cMux_1a0bb6bcecf4a0026ed71819d154f64f36" prot="public" static="no" const="no" explicit="no" inline="no" virt="non-virtual">
        <type>bool</type>
        <definition>bool OpenSkyhawk::I2cMux::select</definition>
        <argsstring>(uint8_t channel, bool force=false)</argsstring>
        <name>select</name>
        <qualifiedname>OpenSkyhawk::I2cMux::select</qualifiedname>
        <param>
          <type>uint8_t</type>
          <declname>channel</declname>
        </param>
        <param>
          <type>bool</type>
          <declname>force</declname>
          <defval>false</defval>
        </param>
        <briefdescription>
<para>Route the bus to one downstream channel. </para>
        </briefdescription>
        <detaileddescription>
<para><parameterlist kind="param"><parameteritem>
<parameternamelist>
<parametername>channel</parametername>
</parameternamelist>
<parameterdescription>
<para>Channel 0–7. Values above 7 are clamped to 7. </para>
</parameterdescription>
</parameteritem>
<parameteritem>
<parameternamelist>
<parametername>force</parametername>
</parameternamelist>
<parameterdescription>
<para>Write the channel byte even if it matches the cache. Use on health/recovery paths: a TCA9548A that reset / power-glitched comes back with no channel selected while the cache still matches, so a plain <ref refid="classOpenSkyhawk_1_1I2cMux_1a0bb6bcecf4a0026ed71819d154f64f36" kindref="member">select()</ref> would skip the write and the branch would stay dark forever. </para>
</parameterdescription>
</parameteritem>
</parameterlist>
<simplesect kind="return"><para>true if the channel is selected (write ACKed, or already current and not forced); false on I2C NAK — also invalidates the cache so the next select re-routes. </para>
</simplesect>
<simplesect kind="note"><para>Writes a single byte (1 &lt;&lt; channel); skipped when channel == last selected unless forced. Callers sharing one mux across several devices MUST call this immediately before each downstream I2C op — an interleaved driver can change the channel. </para>
</simplesect>
</para>
        </detaileddescription>
